    Parses date strings into FuzzyDate instances. The minimum requirement for a valid date string is that a year can be extracted from it.

    Date strings are parsed by iterating over a list of ParseInfo instances, passed in through one of the constructors . A ParseInfo instance specifies how to parse the input string. As soon as a ParseInfo is capable of parsing the date string into a java.time object, the iteration stops. Therefore the more granular ParseInfo instances should come first in the list.

    A FuzzyDateParser can be instantiated with a list of hard-coded ParseInfo instances or with a properties file defining the ParseInfo instances. See the description of the DEFAULT FuzzyDateParser for how to encode ParseInfo instances.

    Note about performance: date parsing is relatively expensive, but the cost does not come from the pattern-matching phase, but from the subsequent creation of a TemporalAccessor object. Therefore the number of ParseInfo instances with which the parser is instantiated does not greatly impact performance.
